<paragraph id="8BD73168FFEC220AA9ADF8F4FA4DF87E" blockId="1.[151,1436,1842,2013]" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEC220AA9ADF8F4FE93F8D3" bold="true" box="[199,322,1878,1904]" pageId="1" pageNumber="172">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Distinguished by the vertical, flattened head, impunctate but wrinkled, at least two times as high as wide, dorsally protruding over the level of the highest point of pronotum; vertex protruding above eye level, width clearly smaller than eye width; labium reaching first abdominal segment; calli strongly swollen and glossy, with few punctures; pronotum large, anterior and posterior lobes distinctly separated, posterior part strongly convex,
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD73168FFEF2209A9FDFF35FC94FF5A" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,249]" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">posterior part and pleurites of thorax with large, deep and dense punctures, posterior margin convex; scutellum strongly tumid; hemelytra hyaline, with sparse punctures, sparsely covered with brown setae; midfemur with four and hindfemur with five trichobothria; tarsi three-segmented.</paragraph>
<caption id="DF1761E0FFEF2209A9FDF9D8FBAFF931" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4756349" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4756349" box="[151,1150,1658,1682]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4756349/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="173" startId="2.[151,250,1658,1682]" targetBox="[163,1427,283,1616]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph id="8BD73168FFEF2209A9FDF9D8FBAFF931" blockId="2.[151,1150,1658,1682]" box="[151,1150,1658,1682]" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEF2209A9FDF9D8FEDCF931" bold="true" box="[151,269,1658,1682]" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">FIGURE 1</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C684AEBFFEF2209A873F9D8FDE3F931" authorityName="Taszakowski, Kim &amp; Herczek" authorityYear="2021" box="[281,562,1658,1682]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Megalofaciatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foliotibialis">
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEF2209A873F9D8FDE3F931" box="[281,562,1658,1682]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">Megalofaciatus foliotibialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: dorsal (
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEF2209ABE6F9D8FD4FF931" bold="true" box="[652,670,1658,1682]" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">A</emphasis>
) and lateral view (
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEF2209AA34F9D8FCBEF931" bold="true" box="[862,879,1658,1682]" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">B</emphasis>
), head in frontal view (
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEF2209AD34F9D8FBA1F931" bold="true" box="[1118,1136,1658,1682]" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">C</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BD73168FFEF2208A9ADF962FCEBFE56" blockId="2.[151,1436,1728,2043]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,151,537]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="174" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEF2209A9ADF962FE88F979" bold="true" box="[199,345,1728,1754]" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">Description.</emphasis>
Male. Body elongate (
<figureCitation id="13532DEDFFEF2209AB32F962FD60F978" box="[600,689,1728,1755]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1658,1682]" captionTargetBox="[163,1427,283,1616]" captionTargetId="figure-63@2.[151,1435,273,1635]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Megalofaciatus foliotibialis: dorsal (A) and lateral view (B), head in frontal view (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4756349" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4756349/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
). Head: 
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEF2209AA65F963FC60F979" box="[783,945,1728,1754]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">in frontal view</emphasis>
: impunctate but wrinkled, height more than two times width, widest at the level of fovea antennalis, vertex protruding above eye level, frons strongly elongated dorso-ventrally, with a distinct longitudinal furrow at middle, extending from the point slightly below lower edge of eye to half its height, sides of the head concave at the base of the eyes, mandibular plate narrow, descending sharply to the base of the clypeus, maxillar plate not visible from the front, concave, fovea antennalis located significantly below the lower rim of the eyes on the posterior part of the maxillar plate, clypeus short, not protruding beyond the plane of the frons. lateral edges of the head with long, protruding setae (
<figureCitation id="13532DEDFFEF2209AAD0F83AFBE6F810" box="[954,1079,1944,1971]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1658,1682]" captionTargetBox="[163,1427,283,1616]" captionTargetId="figure-63@2.[151,1435,273,1635]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Megalofaciatus foliotibialis: dorsal (A) and lateral view (B), head in frontal view (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4756349" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4756349/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">Figs 1B, C</figureCitation>
); 
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEF2209AD21F83BFB3DF811" box="[1099,1260,1944,1970]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">in lateral view</emphasis>
: short, strongly protruding over pronotal collar, exceeding over the highest point of pronotum; antennae cylindrical, segments I and II thick, segments III and IV thin; labium exceeding hindcoxae, second labial segment longest (
<figureCitation id="13532DEDFFEF2209ADA5F842FAF6F858" box="[1231,1319,2016,2043]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1658,1682]" captionTargetBox="[163,1427,283,1616]" captionTargetId="figure-63@2.[151,1435,273,1635]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Megalofaciatus foliotibialis: dorsal (A) and lateral view (B), head in frontal view (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4756349" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4756349/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="173">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
). Pronotal collar with a row of punctures; calli glossy, clearly swollen, separated by a shallow groove, with few small and weak punctures; posterior part of pronotum distinctly punctate, pronotal angle carinate, posterior margin convex; scutellum heart-shaped, with small punctures, strongly tumid, baso-medially depressed; thoracic pleura distinctly punctate (
<figureCitation id="13532DEDFFEE2208A862FEA1FEB0FEBE" box="[264,353,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1658,1682]" captionTargetBox="[163,1427,283,1616]" captionTargetId="figure-63@2.[151,1435,273,1635]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Megalofaciatus foliotibialis: dorsal (A) and lateral view (B), head in frontal view (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4756349" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4756349/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
); evaporatory area triangular, margins straight; ostiolar peritreme small, strongly convex; legs moderately thick and long; midfemur with four (
<figureCitation id="13532DEDFFEE2208ABDDFE85FCC0FEE2" box="[695,785,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1619,1643]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,558,1593]" captionTargetId="figure-171@3.[151,1435,558,1593]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Megalofaciatus foliotibialis: femur of the middle leg in ventrolateral view, showing trichobothrial pattern (A), the femur of the hind leg in ventral (B) and ventrolateral views (C), showing trichobothrial pattern, tarsus of the hind leg, dorsolateral view (D), pretarsus of the foreleg, lateral view (E), hind leg (F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4756353" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4756353/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
), hindfemur with five trichobothria (
<figureCitation id="13532DEDFFEE2208ADC1FE85FAF5FEE2" box="[1195,1316,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1619,1643]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,558,1593]" captionTargetId="figure-171@3.[151,1435,558,1593]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Megalofaciatus foliotibialis: femur of the middle leg in ventrolateral view, showing trichobothrial pattern (A), the femur of the hind leg in ventral (B) and ventrolateral views (C), showing trichobothrial pattern, tarsus of the hind leg, dorsolateral view (D), pretarsus of the foreleg, lateral view (E), hind leg (F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4756353" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4756353/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">Fig. 2B, C</figureCitation>
); hindtibia strongly modified, leaf-shaped (
<figureCitation id="13532DEDFFEE2208AB6DFEE9FDB1FEC6" box="[519,608,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1619,1643]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,558,1593]" captionTargetId="figure-171@3.[151,1435,558,1593]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Megalofaciatus foliotibialis: femur of the middle leg in ventrolateral view, showing trichobothrial pattern (A), the femur of the hind leg in ventral (B) and ventrolateral views (C), showing trichobothrial pattern, tarsus of the hind leg, dorsolateral view (D), pretarsus of the foreleg, lateral view (E), hind leg (F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4756353" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4756353/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">Fig. 2F</figureCitation>
); tarsi three-segmented (
<figureCitation id="13532DEDFFEE2208AA14FEE9FC0BFEC6" box="[894,986,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1619,1643]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,558,1593]" captionTargetId="figure-171@3.[151,1435,558,1593]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Megalofaciatus foliotibialis: femur of the middle leg in ventrolateral view, showing trichobothrial pattern (A), the femur of the hind leg in ventral (B) and ventrolateral views (C), showing trichobothrial pattern, tarsus of the hind leg, dorsolateral view (D), pretarsus of the foreleg, lateral view (E), hind leg (F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4756353" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4756353/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
), claws without apical tooth (
<figureCitation id="13532DEDFFEE2208AC5FFEE9FA41FEC6" box="[1333,1424,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1619,1643]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,558,1593]" captionTargetId="figure-171@3.[151,1435,558,1593]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Megalofaciatus foliotibialis: femur of the middle leg in ventrolateral view, showing trichobothrial pattern (A), the femur of the hind leg in ventral (B) and ventrolateral views (C), showing trichobothrial pattern, tarsus of the hind leg, dorsolateral view (D), pretarsus of the foreleg, lateral view (E), hind leg (F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4756353" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4756353/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">Fig. 2E</figureCitation>
). Abdomen covered with long setae. Genitalia: genital segment with scythe-shaped parameres; left paramere almost as long as right paramere, the sensory lobe of left paramere thicker than that of right one; sensory lobe of left paramere with several long setae, apical process elongate (
<figureCitation id="13532DEDFFEE2208AA43FE15FC52FE72" box="[809,899,439,465]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1525,1549]" captionTargetBox="[207,1379,711,1491]" captionTargetId="figure-199@4.[151,1435,705,1501]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male genitalia of Megalofaciatus foliotibialis: left paramere (A), right paramere (B), aedeagus in dorsal view (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4756357" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4756357/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
); right paramere with knee-shaped sensory lobe (
<figureCitation id="13532DEDFFEE2208A9CAFE79FF26FE56" box="[160,247,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1525,1549]" captionTargetBox="[207,1379,711,1491]" captionTargetId="figure-199@4.[151,1435,705,1501]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male genitalia of Megalofaciatus foliotibialis: left paramere (A), right paramere (B), aedeagus in dorsal view (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4756357" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4756357/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
); endosoma sacciform and membranous (
<figureCitation id="13532DEDFFEE2208ABA0FE79FCFCFE56" box="[714,813,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1525,1549]" captionTargetBox="[207,1379,711,1491]" captionTargetId="figure-199@4.[151,1435,705,1501]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male genitalia of Megalofaciatus foliotibialis: left paramere (A), right paramere (B), aedeagus in dorsal view (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4756357" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4756357/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">Figs. 3C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD73168FFEE2208A9ADFE5DFE4EFDBA" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,537]" box="[199,415,511,537]" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">Female: Unknown.</paragraph>
<caption id="DF1761E0FFEE2208A9FDF9F1FC4FF910" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4756353" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4756353" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4756353/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="174" startId="3.[151,250,1619,1643]" targetBox="[151,1435,558,1593]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph id="8BD73168FFEE2208A9FDF9F1FC4FF910" blockId="3.[151,1436,1619,1715]" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEE2208A9FDF9F1FEC1F9C8" bold="true" box="[151,272,1619,1643]" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">FIGURE 2</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C684AEBFFEE2208A875F9F1FDEBF9C8" authorityName="Taszakowski, Kim &amp; Herczek" authorityYear="2021" box="[287,570,1619,1643]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Megalofaciatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="174" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foliotibialis">
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEE2208A875F9F1FDEBF9C8" box="[287,570,1619,1643]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">Megalofaciatus foliotibialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: femur of the middle leg in ventrolateral view, showing trichobothrial pattern (
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEE2208AC11F9F1FA5CF9C8" bold="true" box="[1403,1421,1619,1643]" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">A</emphasis>
), the femur of the hind leg in ventral (
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEE2208AB74F9D5FDFEF92C" bold="true" box="[542,559,1655,1679]" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">B</emphasis>
) and ventrolateral views (
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEE2208AA2EF9D5FC87F92C" bold="true" box="[836,854,1655,1679]" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">C</emphasis>
), showing trichobothrial pattern, tarsus of the hind leg, dorsolateral view (
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEE2208A83FF939FEB6F910" bold="true" box="[341,359,1691,1715]" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">D</emphasis>
), pretarsus of the foreleg, lateral view (
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEE2208AB93F939FCDBF910" bold="true" box="[761,778,1691,1715]" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">E</emphasis>
), hind leg (
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEE2208AAEAF939FC5EF910" bold="true" box="[896,911,1691,1715]" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">F</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BD73168FFEE2208A9ADF940FAE0F870" blockId="3.[151,1437,1761,2040]" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEE2208A9ADF940FEEAF95F" bold="true" box="[199,315,1762,1788]" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">Remarks.</emphasis>
Affiliation of 
<taxonomicName id="4C684AEBFFEE2208A8B1F943FD58F958" authorityName="Taszakowski, Kim &amp; Herczek" authorityYear="2021" box="[475,649,1761,1787]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Megalofaciatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="174" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEE2208A8B1F943FD58F958" box="[475,649,1761,1787]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">Megalofaciatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to the 
<taxonomicName id="4C684AEBFFEE2208ABBEF943FC43F958" authorityName="Herczek" authorityYear="1993" box="[724,914,1761,1787]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="174" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Gigantometopini">Gigantometopini</taxonomicName>
is clearly confirmed by the following features: compound eyes relatively small, significantly separated from each other, pronotum elongate and at least in part deeply punctate, calli separated by fossa, pronotal collar demarcated by a row of punctures and inflated scutellum (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF94C99FFEE2208AC57F88BFF03F8CB" author="Herczek, A." pageId="3" pageNumber="174" pagination="1 - 86" refId="ref5200" refString="Herczek, A. (1993) Systematic position of Isometopinae Fieb. (Miridae, Heteroptera) and their intrarelationships. Prace Naukowe Uniwersytetu Slaskiego, Katowice, 1357, 1 - 86." type="journal article" year="1993">Herczek 1993</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF94C99FFEE2208A9B7F8ECFE01F8CB" author="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Yamada, K. &amp; Tsai, J. F." box="[221,464,1869,1896]" pageId="3" pageNumber="174" pagination="421 - 439" refId="ref6184" refString="Yasunaga, T., Yamada, K. &amp; Tsai, J. F. (2017) Taxonomic review of the plant bug subfamily Isometopinae for Taiwan and Japanese Southwest Islands, with descriptions of new taxa (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Miridae: Isometopinae). Zootaxa, 4365 (4), 421 - 439. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4365.4.3" type="journal article" year="2017">
Yasunaga 
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEE2208A83BF8ECFE5AF8C4" box="[337,395,1869,1895]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
). Until now, it was believed that 
<taxonomicName id="4C684AEBFFEE2208AA22F8EFFBD7F8C4" authorityName="Herczek" authorityYear="1993" box="[840,1030,1869,1895]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="174" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Gigantometopini">Gigantometopini</taxonomicName>
possess five or six trichobothria on both midfemur and hindfemur (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF94C99FFEE2208A895F8D0FD22F82F" author="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Yamada, K. &amp; Tsai, J. F." box="[511,755,1905,1932]" pageId="3" pageNumber="174" pagination="421 - 439" refId="ref6184" refString="Yasunaga, T., Yamada, K. &amp; Tsai, J. F. (2017) Taxonomic review of the plant bug subfamily Isometopinae for Taiwan and Japanese Southwest Islands, with descriptions of new taxa (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Miridae: Isometopinae). Zootaxa, 4365 (4), 421 - 439. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4365.4.3" type="journal article" year="2017">
Yasunaga 
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEE2208AB1FF8D0FD7EF828" box="[629,687,1905,1931]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF94C99FFEE2208AB95F8D3FBC6F82F" author="Taszakowski, A. &amp; Kim, J. &amp; Damken, C. &amp; Wahab, R. A. &amp; Herczek, A. &amp; Jung, S." box="[767,1047,1905,1932]" pageId="3" pageNumber="174" pagination="71 - 89" refId="ref5842" refString="Taszakowski, A., Kim, J., Damken, C., Wahab, R. A., Herczek, A. &amp; Jung, S. (2020) Two new genera and species of the Gigantometopini (Hemiptera, Heteroptera, Miridae, Isometopinae) from Borneo with remarks on the distribution of the tribe. ZooKeys, 941, 71 - 89. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 941.47432" type="journal article" year="2020">
Taszakowski 
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFEE2208AAF2F8D0FC03F828" box="[920,978,1905,1931]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">et al.</emphasis>
2020
</bibRefCitation>
). However, the described genus is characterised by the presence of four trichobothria on midfemur and five trichobothria on hindfemur. Therefore, it seems that the number of trichobothria on midfemur is more varied in this tribe, ranging from four to six.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD73168FFEE220FA9ADF87FFAABFEBE" blockId="3.[151,1437,1761,2040]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1436,151,429]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="175" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">
The newly described genus is very characteristic and difficult to confuse with other genera of the tribe, from which it is clearly distinguished by the set of features mentioned in the diagnosis. 
<taxonomicName id="4C684AEBFFE9220FAD25FF35FB2CFF12" authorityName="Taszakowski, Kim &amp; Herczek" authorityYear="2021" box="[1103,1277,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Megalofaciatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFE9220FAD25FF35FB2CFF12" box="[1103,1277,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="175">Megalofaciatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the second largest member of the tribe, with only the single known specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="4C684AEBFFE9220FAAE7FF19FA4DFF76" authority="Schwartz &amp; Schuh, 1990" authorityName="Schwartz &amp; Schuh" authorityYear="1990" box="[909,1436,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Gigantometopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rossi">
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFE9220FAAE7FF19FB50FF77" box="[909,1153,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="175">Gigantometopus rossi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFF94C99FFE9220FADE2FF19FA4DFF76" author="Schwartz, M. D. &amp; Schuh, R. T." box="[1160,1436,187,213]" pageId="4" pageNumber="175" pagination="9 - 13" refId="ref5749" refString="Schwartz, M. D. &amp; Schuh, R. T. (1990) The world's largest Isometopine, Gigantometopus rossi, new genus and new species (Heteroptera: Miridae). Journal New York Entomological Society, 98 (1), 9 - 13." type="journal article" year="1990">Schwartz &amp; Schuh, 1990</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
being larger (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF94C99FFE9220FA847FF7DFD94FF5A" author="Schwartz, M. D. &amp; Schuh, R. T." box="[301,581,223,249]" pageId="4" pageNumber="175" pagination="9 - 13" refId="ref5749" refString="Schwartz, M. D. &amp; Schuh, R. T. (1990) The world's largest Isometopine, Gigantometopus rossi, new genus and new species (Heteroptera: Miridae). Journal New York Entomological Society, 98 (1), 9 - 13." type="journal article" year="1990">Schwartz &amp; Schuh 1990</bibRefCitation>
). The most distinctive feature of genus is the shape of the head. Its height is more than two times width, and in the front view, it is clearly concave at the level of the lower edge of the eyes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD73168FFE9220FA9ADFE85FD3EFEC6" blockId="4.[151,1436,151,429]" pageId="4" pageNumber="175">
Strongly modified, leaf-shaped hindtibia of 
<taxonomicName id="4C684AEBFFE9220FABD6FE85FC25FEE2" authorityName="Taszakowski, Kim &amp; Herczek" authorityYear="2021" box="[700,1012,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Megalofaciatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foliotibialis">
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFE9220FABD6FE85FC25FEE2" box="[700,1012,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="175">Megalofaciatus foliotibialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are a completely new and surprising feature at the tribal, subfamily, and even family level.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD73168FFE9220FA9ADFECDFEB5FE0E" blockId="4.[151,1436,151,429]" pageId="4" pageNumber="175">
<emphasis id="B91CED7AFFE9220FA9ADFECDFE9FFE2A" bold="true" box="[199,334,367,393]" pageId="4" pageNumber="175">Etymology.</emphasis>
Combined from Latinized from Greek adjective μεγάλε—“big” and Latin word facies—“face”; gender masculine.
</paragraph>
